article.headline: Phoenix ends two-game losing streak
article.story:
PHOENIX (AP) -- Although Diana Taurasi knew plenty of old friends
would be aware of her latest performance as a pro, and she didn't
lose her focus.

Former UConn All-American Taurasi had 17 points and five assists
Wednesday to lead the Phoenix Mercury past the Connecticut Sun
75-59. The Sun play just 30 miles from Storrs, where Taurasi was
the biggest star for three-time national champion UConn.

"I know everybody at home was watching," said Taurasi, who
scored 26 points in the Mercury's season-opening victory May 22
over the Sun in Uncasville, Conn. "But it's not that big of a
deal."

What was a big deal was the 13-1 run by Phoenix to a 56-40 lead
with 10:08 left Wednesday. The Sun managed only a free throw by
Wendy Palmer in a stretch of 5:46 and got no closer than 10 points
thereafter.

"I can't find much good at all about the game," Connecticut
coach Mike Thibault said. "They beat us on both ends of the
court."

Plenette Pierson added 13 points and 10 rebounds for the
Mercury, who ended a two-game losing streak.

Nykesha Sales scored 23 points on 10-of-14 shooting to lead the
Sun, who have lost two straight after winning three in a row.

"We had little breakdowns, but we were really tough in the
second half," Phoenix coach Carrie Graf said. "That really turned
the tide for us."

Connecticut shot over 50 percent for the first 28 minutes, but
missed 11 of its last 16 shots. The Sun also committed 16
turnovers, including four in the decisive run by the Mercury.

Penny Taylor scored 13 of her 15 points in the second half for
Phoenix, which also outrebounded Connecticut 26-20.

"We were getting killed on the boards," Connecticut's Katie
Douglas said. "We can't have that. We just missed a lot of easy
shots and turned the ball over."

Phoenix held Taj McWilliams-Franklin and Palmer to a total of 11
points, about half their combined average. Connecticut, the
third-highest scoring team in the league, was held 10 points under
its average.

Douglas added 11 points for the Sun.

Sales had 13 points and the Sun made 15 of 23 shots in the first
half, but had 10 turnovers and fell behind 37-33 at the break.

"In the first half, they came out firing, shooting almost 70
percent," Taylor said. "We knew they couldn't keep it up the
whole game and we were doing the right things so we stuck with it
and we were very physical and aggressive with our defense."

Phoenix shot 52.5 percent (31-for-59), led by Taurasi's 6-for-8
performance.
